John Edward: The Language Skills Needed for the World’s Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their scientific achievements — in 2018 they were able to boast the following excellent results of exams, individual and collective successes in sports, arts, music and other endeavors.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) schools, attended by more than 30,000 students across Scotland, they aim to provide the best level of services to students and parents.
The aim of the independent schools is to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career paths and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that has the opportunity to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another man in a language he understands, then it’s up to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely only on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that the languages occupy the first place in league rankings, with the highest rates of susceptibility occurring in the case of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who learned foreign languages received a higher A rating.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 per cent of students received a higher A rating in Mandarin, and 72 per cent of German learners, 69 per cent of French learners and 63 per cent of Spanish learners also received an A rating.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as the necessary skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, language learning, as subjects to choose from, is conducted in the same scope as STEM subjects (narrow science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) within the framework of teaching programs in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UK Commission for Employment and Skills) found that, due to the difficulty in occupying vacant jobs by employers, 17 percent of the candidates’ language skills were inadequate.
That is why language skills are becoming increasingly necessary to prepare young people for the start of a career in the field of linguistics.
These skills are necessary in a globalized world with an increasing number of jobs requiring language skills, and
The ability to stay alive, like learning a second language, will have a huge advantage in the future — regardless of the defensive path of professional development.
The possibility of direct communication with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults, 75% of them were unable to speak in a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by 1 percent of the population.
Therefore, investing in the teaching of foreign languages is so important for today’s children.
The knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children a greater chance of finding the appropriate employment.
In Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages taught in it.
Many schools will focus on more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be most important for the UK in the 2020s, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interest of the child, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from, which will be taught by specialized didactic staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are involved in creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed—regardless of what the future holds for them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in an international business environment, languages still play a key role in the future of the country, and so it must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be treated as ‘international communication skills’. . . .
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a great choice, diversity and level of choice.
That's just right.
