Harvard students are taking part in a course on the appropriate long-term rest.
The new course at Harvard University, which took place this year, provided all students with more sleep, which was intended to combat the growing macho culture, which consisted of being taught by “night-time caffeine-fueled students.”
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea of the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
To create the course, he was inspired to make a speech about the influence of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the end of the speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why is this being told to me only now that I’m in my final year of studies?’
She said that no one had ever told her about the meaning of the dream, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
During the course, which took place for the first time this year, it is explained to students how good sleep-related habits help achieve good results in science and sports, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University Health Service, said the course was set to be introduced after it was found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes a picture of the room in the academy, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercises and books to get information about the impact of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects sports outcomes, as well as how important it is to maintain a healthy lifestyle.
In another section, participants learn how a long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their day-to-day routine.
“We know that this will not cause an immediate change in student behavior.
But we believe that they have the right to know — just as everyone has the right to know what health effects smoking cigarettes has with them,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride from “all-night science” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means an increasing problem of lack of sleep.
Ensuring a sufficient amount of good quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even allowing them to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go through a state of mind.
