HIV/Aids: China reports 14 percent increase in new cases
China has announced a 14 percent increase in the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected by this problem, as reported by the country’s health service.
In the second quarter of 2018, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of new cases have been transmitted through sexual intercourse, which means a change from the past.
Traditionally, the HIV virus spreads rapidly in some parts of China as a result of transfusion of infected blood.
However, the number of people infected with the HIV virus in this way was almost completely reduced, as Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, year by year, the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Transmitting HIV through sex is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against people from the LGBT community is common.
Taking into account the conservative values of the country, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of transmission of the disease result from insufficient protection when having sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has provided universal access to HIV drugs as part of efforts to combat this problem.
